[normal]The 
[normal]Highway Code
[normal] on Level Crossings: rules 
[normal]291 – 299
[normal]291. [bold]A level crossing is where a road crosses a railway or tramway line. Approach and cross it with care. Never drive onto a 
[normal]crossing until the road is clear on the other side and do not get too close to the car in front. Never stop or park on, or near, a crossing.
[normal]292. Overhead electric lines[bold] it is dangerous to touch overhead electric lines. You 
[normal]MUST[bold] obey the safe height warning road signs and you should not continue forward onto the railway if your vehicle touches any height barrier or bells. The clearance available is usually 5 metres (16 feet 6 inches) but may be lower. 
[normal]Laws RTA 1988 sect 36, TSRGD[bold] 2002 reg 17(5)[bold]293. Controlled Crossings.[bold] Most crossings have traffic light signals with a steady amber light, twin flashing red stop lights (
[normal]download ‘Light signals controlling traffic’ (PDF, 82KB)
[normal] and 
[normal]‘Traffic signs’ (PDF, 486KB)
[normal]) and an audible alarm for pedestrians. They may have full, half or no barriers.
[normal]294. Railway telephones.[bold] If you are driving a large or slow- moving vehicle, a long, low vehicle with a risk of grounding, or herding animals, a train could arrive before you are clear of the crossing. You 
[normal]MUST[bold] obey any sign instruct
[normal]ing you to use the railway telephone to obtain permission to cross. You 
[normal]MUST[bold] also telephone when clear of the 
[normal]crossing if requested to do so: 
[normal]Laws RTA 1988 sect 36 &amp; TSRGD regs 10 &amp; 16(1)[bold]295. Crossings without traffic lights.[bold] Vehicles should stop and wait
[normal] at the barrier or gate when it begins to close and not cross until the barrier or gate opens.
[normal]296. User-operated gates or barriers.[bold] Some crossings have ‘Stop’ signs and small red and green lights. You 
[normal]MUST NOT[bold] cross when the red light is showing, only cro
[normal]ss if the green light is on. If crossing with a vehicle, you should
[normal]297. [bold]If there are no lights, follow the procedure in Rule 295. Stop, look both ways and listen before you cross. If there is a railway telephone, always use it to contact the signal operator to make sure it is safe to 
[normal]cross. Inform the signal operator again when you are clear of the crossing.
[normal]298. Open crossings.[bold] These have no gates, barriers, attendant or traffic lights but will have a ‘Give Way’ sign. You should look both ways, listen and make sure there is no train c
[normal]oming before you cross. 
[normal]299. Incidents and breakdowns.[bold] If your vehicle breaks down, or if you have an incident on a crossing you should
