[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Annex [bold]D[bold]Transport Select Committee[bold]Inquiry into Safety at Level Crossings[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Theory test case study example
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]You are driving in the left-hand lane on a three-lane dual carriageway subject to the national speed limit.  It is a windy day 
[normal]and you are towing a small trailer which begins to snake. Ahead, in the centre lane, there is a slower moving motorcyclist that you intend to overtake.
[normal]You move into the center lane and the motorcyclist moves into the left-hand lane.  
[normal]After leaving the du
[normal]al carriageway you approach a half barrier level crossing. Flashing red lights are showing. Two trains pass before the barrier goes up. Further along the road you stop in heavy traffic. The car behind runs into the back of you. The driver is displaying a h
[normal]elp pennant. You are carrying a red warning triangle.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]What should you do after seeing the first train pass?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Wait for the lights to go off and the barriers open
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Look left, right, left, and proceeds if clear
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Look right, left, right, and proceed if clear
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Wait for the amber light and zigzag around the barriers
